Analyzing hurricane tracks¶

In the previous notebooks we you saw

  1. downloading historic hurricane datasets using Python
  2. cleaning and merging hurricane observations using DASK
  3. aggregating point observations into hurricane tracks using ArcGIS GeoAnalytics

In this notebook you will analyze the aggregated tracks to answer important questions about prevalance of hurricanes, their seasonality and investigate whether their severity has increased over time.

The track duration and length columns need to be projected to units (days, hours, miles) that are meaningful for analysis.

In [11]:
all_hurricanes_df['TRACK_DURATION_hrs'] = all_hurricanes_df['TRACK_DURATION'] / 3600000
all_hurricanes_df['TRACK_DURATION_days'] = all_hurricanes_df['TRACK_DURATION'] / (3600000*24)
In [13]:
# convert meters to miles
all_hurricanes_df['TRACK_length_mi'] = all_hurricanes_df['Shape__Length'] / 1609.344

Does the number of hurricanes increase with time?¶

To understand if number of hurricanes have increased over time, we plot a histogram of the MIN_Season column.

In [65]:
ax = sns.distplot(all_hurricanes_df['MIN_Season'], kde=False, bins=50)
ax.set_title('Number of hurricanes recorded over time')
Out[65]:
Text(0.5,1,'Number of hurricanes recorded over time')

The number of hurricanes recorded increases steadily until 1970. This could be due to advances in geospatial technologies allowing scientists to better monitor hurricanes. However, after 1970 we notice a reduction in the number of hurricanes. This is in line with what scientists observe and predict.

How many hurricanes occuer per basin and sub basin?¶

About 7 basins and a number of sub basins have been identified. The snippet below plots the frequency of hurricanes by basin and sub basin.

In [28]:
fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(12,5))

basin_ax = all_hurricanes_df['ANY_Basin'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', ax=ax1[0])
basin_ax.set_title('Number of hurricanes per basin')
# basin_ax.tick_params(axis='x', labelrotation=65)
basin_ax.set_xticklabels(['Western Pacific', 'South Indian', 'North Atlantic',
                          'Eastern Pacicifc', 'North Indian','Southern Pacific',
                          'South Atlantic'])

sub_basin_ax = all_hurricanes_df['ANY_Sub_basin'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', ax=ax1[1])
sub_basin_ax.set_title('Number of hurricanes per sub basin')
sub_basin_ax.set_xticklabels(['MM','North Atlantic','Bay of Bengal','Western Australia',
                             'Eastern Australia', 'Carribean Sea', 'Gulf of Mexico',
                             'Arabian Sea', 'Central Pacific'])
sub_basin_ax.tick_params()

Thus, most hurricanes occur in Wester Pacific basin. This is the region that is east of China, Phillipines and rest of South East Asia. This is followed by South Indian which spans from west of Australia to east of Southern Africa. North Atlantic basin which is the source of hurricanes in the continental United States ranks as the third busiest hurricane basin.

Is there a seasonality in the occurrence of hurricanes?¶

Hurricanes happen when water temperatures (Sea Surface Temperature SST) are warm. Solar incidence is one of the key factors affecting SST and this typically happens during summer months. However, summer happens during different months in northern and southern hemispheres. To visualize this seasonality, we need to group our data by month as well as basin. Thus the snippet below creates a multilevel index grouper in Pandas

In [147]:
# Create a grouper object
grouper = all_hurricanes_df.START_DATETIME.dt.month_name()

# use grouper along with basin name to create a multilevel groupby object
hurr_by_basin = all_hurricanes_df.groupby([grouper,'ANY_Basin'], as_index=True)
hurr_by_basin_month = hurr_by_basin.count()[['COUNT_', 'MIN_pressure_m']]
hurr_by_basin_month.head()
Out[147]:
COUNT_ MIN_pressure_m
START_DATETIME ANY_Basin
April NA 5 5
NI 41 41
SI 241 241
SP 93 93
WP 82 82

Now we turn the index into columns. Then add the month column back, but this time we will help Pandas understand how to sort months other than by alphabetical order.

In [148]:
# turn index into columns
hurr_by_basin_month.reset_index(inplace=True)
hurr_by_basin_month.drop('MIN_pressure_m', axis=1, inplace=True)
hurr_by_basin_month.columns = ['month', 'basin', 'count']
hurr_by_basin_month.head()
Out[148]:
month basin count
0 April NA 5
1 April NI 41
2 April SI 241
3 April SP 93
4 April WP 82
In [154]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(15,7))
month_order = ['January','February', 'March','April','May','June',
              'July','August','September','October','November','December']

sns.barplot(x='month', y='count', hue='basin', data=hurr_by_basin_month, ax=ax,
            order=month_order)
Out[154]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x1a20962e10>

The bars in green represent the number of hurricanes in Sounth Indian ocean which spans from west of Australia to east of southern Africa while the purple bars are for Western Pacific which spans east of China and blue bars for North Atlantic. The sinusoidal nature of these bars show the charateristic offset in summer between northern and southern hemispheres. The orange bars represent North Indian hurricanes which is dominated by monsoon effect and is seen to be prevalant for most part of the year.

Manage missing sesnsor data¶

Sensor measurements such as wind speed, atmospheric pressure, eye diameter, suffer from missing values and outliers.

In [155]:
all_hurricanes_df.shape
Out[155]:
(12256, 19)

Visualize missing records¶

An easy way to visualize missing records is to hack the heatmap of seaborn library to display missing records. The snippet below shows missing records in yellow color.

In [223]:
missing_data_viz = all_hurricanes_df.replace(0,np.NaN)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
missing_data_ax = sns.heatmap(missing_data_viz[['MAX_wind_knots',
                                 'MIN_pressure_m','MAX_eye_dia_mi',
                                 'TRACK_DURATION_hrs']].isnull(), cbar=False,
                             cmap='viridis')
missing_data_ax.set_ylabel('Years')
missing_data_ax.set_title('Missing values (yellow) visualized as a heatmap')
Out[223]:
Text(0.5,1,'Missing values (yellow) visualized as a heatmap')

Missing value imputation¶

Technique 1: Drop missing values

In [159]:
hurricanes_nona = missing_data_viz.dropna(subset=['MAX_wind_knots','MIN_pressure_m'])
hurricanes_nona.shape
Out[159]:
(3352, 19)

Technique 2: Fill using median value

In [160]:
fill_values = {'MAX_wind_knots': missing_data_viz['MAX_wind_knots'].median(),
                'MIN_pressure_m': missing_data_viz['MIN_pressure_m'].median(),
              'TRACK_DURATION_hrs': missing_data_viz['TRACK_DURATION_hrs'].median()}
hurricanes_fillna = missing_data_viz.fillna(value=fill_values)

Technique 3: Fill by interpolating between existing values

In [224]:
hurricanes_ipl = missing_data_viz
hurricanes_ipl['MAX_wind_knots'] = hurricanes_ipl['MAX_wind_knots'].interpolate()
hurricanes_ipl['MIN_pressure_m'] = hurricanes_ipl['MIN_pressure_m'].interpolate()
hurricanes_ipl['TRACK_DURATION_hrs'] = hurricanes_ipl['TRACK_DURATION_hrs'].interpolate()

Visualize all 3 techniques

In [162]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, sharex=True, figsize=(15,5))
fig.suptitle('Comparing effects of missing value imputations on Wind speed column', 
             fontsize=15)

hurricanes_nona['MAX_wind_knots'].plot(kind='hist', ax=ax[0], bins=35)
hurricanes_fillna['MAX_wind_knots'].plot(kind='hist', ax=ax[1], bins=35)
hurricanes_ipl['MAX_wind_knots'].plot(kind='hist', ax=ax[2], bins=35)
for a in ax:
    a.set_xlabel('Wind Speed')
In [163]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, sharex=True, figsize=(15,5))
fig.suptitle('Comparing effects of missing value imputations on Pressure column', 
             fontsize=15)

hurricanes_nona['MIN_pressure_m'].plot(kind='hist', ax=ax[0])
hurricanes_fillna['MIN_pressure_m'].plot(kind='hist', ax=ax[1])
hurricanes_ipl['MIN_pressure_m'].plot(kind='hist', ax=ax[2])
for a in ax:
    a.set_xlabel('Atmospheric Pressure')

Fill using interpolation preserves shape of the original distribution. So it will be used
